%N A085623 Let p = n-th prime; a(n) = number of pairs (i,j) with 0 < i < p, 0 < j < p such that i*j == 1 mod p and i and j have opposite parity.
%C A085623 If we let p = 2*n+1 run through all odd numbers >=3 and consider only i coprime to p, the sequence becomes 0, 2, 0, 4, 4, 6, 0, 10, 4, 4, 12, 14, 8, 18, 4, 12, 12, 14, 8, 18... - _R. J. Mathar_, Aug 07 2010
%D A085623 R. K. Guy, Unsolved Problems in Number Theory, F12.
%H A085623 T. D. Noe, <a href="/A085623/b085623.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..1000</a>
%H A085623 Yaming Lu and Yuan Yi, <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.4064/aa142-2-7">On the generalization of the D. H. Lehmer problem II</a>, Acta Arithm. vol 142 no 2 (2010), 179-186.
%H A085623 Yuan Yi and Zhang Wen-peng, <a href="https://doi.org/10.2206/kyushujm.56.235">On the generalization of a problem of D. H. Lehmer</a>, Kyushu J. Math., 56 (2002) 235-241; MR 2003g:11112.
%e A085623 For p = 13, the pairs are (2,7), (5,8), (6,11) and their reversals. So a(6) = 6.
%t A085623 f[n_] := Length[ Select[ Mod[ Flatten[ Table[i*j, {j, 2, n - 1}, {i, j - 1, 1, -2}], 1], n], # == 1 & ]]; 2Table[ f[ Prime[n]], {n, 2, 70}]
